## Assistant

Yes. This is **very feasible**, and it is more than a token-saving optimization—it could become one of the genuinely differentiated parts of the product.

But the right design is **not** “put all PowerFactory data in the prompt” and not “use Graphify unchanged.”

It is:

> Build a persistent, queryable **power-system model graph** from PowerFactory, then let the agent request small, relevant subgraphs instead of repeatedly rediscovering the model.

## What Graphify is actually doing

Graphify builds a persistent graph, then lets an agent ask targeted questions:

```text
Raw repository files
→ build persistent graph once
→ query a small relevant subgraph later
→ avoid repeatedly reading/searching the whole repository
```

It exposes operations like:

```text
query_graph(question)
get_node(node)
get_neighbors(node)
shortest_path(a, b)
```

It also distinguishes facts directly extracted from source from inferred links. That last part is worth copying.

Sources: [Graphify](https://graphify.net/), [Graphify GitHub repository](https://github.com/Graphify-Labs/graphify)

For your product:

```text
PowerFactory project
→ extract topology and active configuration
→ build a Power System Knowledge Graph
→ query a scoped graph slice
→ use PowerFactory only when fresh values are required
```

## Why this maps unusually well to PowerFactory

A power-system model is already a graph.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Grid --> Substation
    Substation --> BusA[Bus]
    BusA --> Line
    Line --> BusB[Bus]
    BusB --> Transformer
    Transformer --> BusC[Bus]
    BusC --> Load
    BusC --> PV[PV Generator]
```

PowerFactory already has the source entities needed:

- grids;
- substations;
- terminals/buses;
- lines and cables;
- transformers;
- switches, couplers, and fuses;
- loads, generators, PV systems, shunts, and external grids;
- areas and zones;
- study cases;
- operational scenarios;
- grid variants and stages;
- calculation results.

This is not speculative. `powerfactory-tools` can export active grid data into three distinct Power System Data Model artifacts:

1. **Topology** — structural network assets and connectivity;
2. **Topology case** — switching state;
3. **Steady-state case** — active operating points.

Source: [`powerfactory-tools` export documentation](https://github.com/ieeh-tu-dresden/powerfactory-tools#exporter)

That is nearly the exact input you need.

DIgSILENT also explicitly describes its model as a hierarchical, object-oriented database with multiple operation scenarios, study cases, variations, versions, and configurable calculation definitions.

Source: [DIgSILENT — Network Model Management](https://www.digsilent.de/en/data-management.html)

## The important distinction: structural context vs live state

Your instinct is right, but the graph cannot become the source of truth for everything.

There are two kinds of context:

| Context type | Examples | Can be cached? |
|---|---|---|
| **Structural context** | What connects to Bus 17? Which transformer feeds this load? What assets exist in Area North? | Yes, aggressively |
| **Configuration context** | Active study case, scenario, grid variation, switch state | Yes, but only with a precise scope/version |
| **Live simulation state** | Bus voltage, transformer loading, convergence, violation results | Only as a timestamped snapshot; refresh before consequential actions |

So the model should not say:

> “The graph says bus B17 is at 0.93 p.u., so I’ll change transformer T4.”

It should say:

> “The graph identifies T4 as electrically adjacent to B17. Before modifying anything, I’ll run or inspect the current study-case result.”

That gives you speed **without stale-data risk**.

## The graph schema

I would build a typed engineering graph—not generic GraphRAG.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
