## How I would build it

### Phase 1 — Build a deterministic model index

Use the PowerFactory API or `powerfactory-tools` to export the current calculation-relevant grid.

```python
data = pfi.compile_powerfactory_data(grid)

topology = exporter.create_topology(...)
topology_case = exporter.create_topology_case(...)
steady_state_case = exporter.create_steadystate_case(...)
```

Then transform those objects into your own graph format.

For the initial version, use:

```text
NetworkX graph in memory
+ SQLite or JSON snapshot for persistence
```

Do **not** bring in Neo4j for Build Week. It adds operational complexity without making the demo better.

### Phase 2 — Add a stable context identity

Every graph must be scoped by more than the project name.

```text
context_id =
    project
    + active study case
    + active scenario
    + active grid variants/stages
    + active grids
    + model/index revision
```

For example:

```text
Regional Planning
/ Summer Peak
/ 2030 Demand
/ Solar Expansion
/ rev 41
```

The exact same line or load can have different operational values depending on the active study case, scenario, and variation. PowerFactory’s model-management design makes this explicit.

### Phase 3 — Separate static and dynamic graph layers

```text
Static topology graph
    buses, lines, transformers, assets, containment

Configuration overlay
    active study case, scenario, variation, switch state

Result overlay
    run ID, convergence status, bus voltages, loading, violations

Change overlay
    proposed or applied mutations, before/after values, approval state
```

This lets you keep topology cached while adding a new result snapshot after every simulation.

### Phase 4 — Update incrementally after agent actions

If the agent scales 184 loads, do not rebuild the entire graph.

```text
Agent applies change
→ record ChangeSet
→ update the 184 affected nodes
→ run load flow
→ attach a new CalculationRun + ResultSnapshot
→ recompute only relevant violation nodes
```

That is a real agent memory system, except it is tied to engineering state and has an audit trail.

## The hard part: stale context

This is the main design constraint.

Your graph will become stale if:

- a human changes the PowerFactory model manually;
- the user switches study case in the GUI;
- another engineer edits a shared model;
- a scenario or grid variant changes;
- an external process modifies the database.

You should **not** pretend the graph is always current.

Instead, add freshness levels:

```text
freshness = "cached"
freshness = "verified"
freshness = "live"
```

| Level | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `cached` | Read from the persisted graph; good for topology exploration. |
| `verified` | Confirmed the active PowerFactory configuration still matches the graph scope. |
| `live` | Read from PowerFactory or produced by the latest calculation run. |

Before applying a mutation, always require `verified` or `live`.

```text
Graph says this transformer is adjacent to Bus 17
→ verify active study case / scenario / variant
→ read live transformer settings
→ preview proposed change
→ request approval
→ apply
```

For the MVP, the simplest reliable policy is:

> The agent is the only process making model changes during a session. If a human changes the model manually, they click **Refresh Model Context**.

Later, you can investigate a more automatic project-version or fingerprint-based invalidation mechanism.

